Task 1 Problem 3:

Code 

def custom_log_labels(x):
    return [f'{int(i / 1000)}k' if i >= 16000 else str(int(i)) for i in x]

(ggplot(cleandf1, aes(x = "income", y = "life_exp", size = "population", fill = "four_regions"))
+ geom_hline(yintercept=[20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90], color='lightgray', size=0.5) 
+ geom_vline(xintercept=[500, 1000, 2000, 4000, 8000, 16000, 32000, 64000], color='lightgray', size=0.5) 
+ geom_point(alpha = 1)
+ scale_x_log10(breaks = (500, 1000, 2000, 4000, 8000, 16000, 32000, 64000), limits=(500,64000), labels=custom_log_labels)
+ scale_y_continuous(limits=(20,90), breaks = np.arange(20,91,10))
+ scale_size(range=(2,30))
+ guides(size=False)
+ theme_classic()  # Removes the gray background
+ annotate('text', x=5000, y=50, label='2010', size=200, color='gray', alpha=0.2)
+ labs(x='Income', y='Life expectancy', fill = "World Regions")
+ annotate('text', x=5000, y=90, label='INCOME LEVEL 1             LEVEL 2             LEVEL 3            LEVEL 4', size=16, color='gray', ha='center')
+ theme(figure_size= (14,6))
+ scale_fill_manual(values = custom_colors)
+ annotate("text", x=500, y=90, label='years', angle=90, color="gray")
+ annotate("text", x=35000, y=20, label='per person (GDP/capita, PPPS inflation-adjusted)', color="gray")
)

In this second plot, I created a histogram comparing income levels across different countries in four different regions in the world using facet wrap. This plot is much simpler and effective at comparing income across the four different world regions, however, it lacks the ability to compare income with life expectancy across the four regions, which is what the first plot does well. Overall, the first plot offers more insights as it is able to compare more variables like life expectancy and population, than the histogram plot. In the scatterplot, the viewers are able to see a postive trend between income and life expectancy. In terms of the histogram plot, I believe it is easier to visualize which region has the highest income compared to the scatterplot. Overall, both plots are highly informative, but the scatterplot provides more insights as it is able compare the additional variables of life expectancy and population.

Task 2 Problem 3:

Code 
cleandf2 = df2.dropna()
cleandf2['energy'] = cleandf2['energy'].str.replace('k', '000')
cleandf2['energy'] = cleandf2['energy'].astype(float)

(ggplot(cleandf2, aes(x = "exports", y = "imports", size = "energy", fill = "four_regions"))
+ geom_vline(xintercept=[20, 40, 60, 80, 100, 120, 140, 160, 180, 200, 220], color='lightgray', size=0.5) 
+ geom_hline(yintercept=[50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300, 350, 400], color='lightgray', size=0.5) 
+ geom_point(alpha = 1)
+ scale_x_continuous(breaks = (20, 40, 60, 80, 100, 120, 140, 160, 180, 200, 220), limits=(0,220))
+ scale_y_continuous(breaks =(50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300, 350, 400), limits = (0,400))
+ scale_size(range=(2,30))
+ guides(size=False)
+ theme_classic() 
+ annotate('text', x=100, y=200, label='1997', size=200, color='gray', alpha=0.2)
+ labs(x='Exports (\% of GDP)', y='Imports(\% of GDP)', fill = "World Regions")
+ theme(figure_size= (14,6))
+ scale_fill_manual(values = custom_colors))

Code 
#Task 2 New Geometry
(ggplot(cleandf2,
aes(
  x = "imports",
  fill = "four_regions"
))
+ geom_density(alpha=0.4)
+theme_classic()
+ scale_fill_manual(values = custom_colors)
+ labs(x='Imports', y='Density', fill = "World Regions")
+ scale_x_continuous(breaks = (20, 60, 100, 140, 180, 220), limits=(0,160))
)

In this second plot, I created a density plot showing the distribution of imports across different world regions. This density plot is a much simpler visualization than the scatterplot as its focusing entirely on the distribution of one variable, imports, and how they vary across region. Compared to the scatterplot, I think the denisty plot is a much worse visualization as it lacks the additional variables that the scatterplot visualizes like exports and energy. The scatterplot is able to clearly visualize the relationship between multiple variables (imports, exports, energy and region), and provides a much detailed representation of the data. If the goal is to compare the relationship between imports and exports for each world region, I would definietly argue the scatterplot does a much better job of this.

Code 
cleandf3 = df3.dropna()


(ggplot(cleandf3, aes(x = "internet_users", y = "gdp", size = "income", fill = "four_regions"))
+ geom_vline(xintercept=[10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90], color='lightgray', size=0.5) 
+ geom_hline(yintercept=[200, 500, 1000, 2000, 5000, 10000, 20000, 50000, 100000], color='lightgray', size=0.5) 
+ geom_point(alpha = 1)
+ scale_x_continuous(breaks = (10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90), limits=(0,90))
+ scale_y_continuous(trans = 'log2', 
    breaks =(200, 500, 1000, 2000, 5000, 10000, 20000, 50000, 100000), 
    limits = (0,200000), 
    labels=(200, 500, 1000, 2000, 5000, '10k', '20k', '50k', '100k'))
+ scale_size(range=(2,30))
+ guides(size=False)
+ theme_classic() 
+ annotate('text', x=45, y=5000, label='2001', size=200, color='gray', alpha=0.2)
+ labs(x='Individuals using the Internet', y='GDP/capita', fill = "World Regions")
+ theme(figure_size= (14,6))
+ scale_fill_manual(values = custom_colors)
+ annotate("text", x=.1, y=50000, label='US$ inflation-adjusted', angle=90, color="gray")
+ annotate("text", x=89, y=200, label='\% of population', color="gray")
)

Task 3 Problem 4:

Code 
#Task 3 New Geometry
(ggplot(cleandf3,
aes(
  x = "internet_users",
  y = "gdp",
  fill = "four_regions"
))
+ geom_boxplot()
+ facet_wrap("four_regions")
+theme_classic()
+ scale_fill_manual(values = custom_colors)
+ labs(x='Individuals using the Internet', y='GDP/capita', fill = "World Regions")
)

In this second plot, I created a box plot comparing the distribution of GDP per capita across different levels of internet usage within each world region. This box plot adds more insights into basic summary statistics for each world region such as the median, quartiles, and any outliers present in the data. In comparing the box plot to the scatterplot, the scatterplot provides a more powerful visualization of the relationship between internet usage and GDP within each region, while also adding in the income variable. The scatterplot provides more insights into the data and additional variables but is more complex to interpret. Overall, I think the scatterplot does a much better job at visualizing the data compared to the box plot.
